Apache has multiple levels of look-ups:
- the `Host:` header is used to send to a specific `<VirtualHost>` section of the configuration;
- if `mod_rewrite` is enabled, it can mangle the request in all possible ways, depending on URI, `Host:` header, and actually any other HTTP header;
- contexts like `<Directory>`, `<Location>`, etc. are used;
- last but not least, there are some special directives like `Alias` and custom handlers, that can alter the request.

When proxying requests, there are at least two schemes:
- `mod_rewrite`'s `RewriteRule` with a `[P]` flag;
- `mod_proxy` with its special directives like `ProxyPass`.

The "easy trick" is split in two parts:
- first, add an extra layer of analysis, to check the URI (instead of only the `Host:` header);
- then, load the complete configuration in RAM, so that lookups like prefix lookups are efficient.

For Hipache, it means two completely new code paths; that's why it's not an easy hack.

